Looking into Bildkite tool chain for Bazel itself, they are using native Bazel feature for authentication: [1]:

  --google_default_credentials

that was added by Yakob Buchgraber in this CL: [2]:

  Also, --auth_enabled (aka --google_default_credentials) is no longer required
  when specifying --auth_credentials (aka --google_credentials).
  So now there's two simple ways to authenticate with Google Cloud:
   * bazel build --google_default_credentials
   * bazel build --google_credentials=creds.json

Unrelated to authentication issue but, Bazel CI implicitly disabling --disk_cache option: [3], that we currently don't:

  # Some projects set --disk_cache in their project-specific bazelrc, which we never want on
  # CI, so let's just disable it explicitly.
  "--disk_cache=",

So that if we figure out how to use RBE from GCP worker node, we have to disable disk_cache entirely.

[1] https://github.com/bazelbuild/continuous-integration/blob/master/buildkite/bazelci.py#L1403-L1409
[2] https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/commit/8a7c63e76320b1ae8eafc1a44d82d1214e1bfdb0
[3] https://github.com/bazelbuild/continuous-integration/blob/master/buildkite/bazelci.py#L1473-L1475

@Luca I'm procrastinating to publish custom GCP Ubuntu 18.04 image to docker hub registry. Is it really necessary? If any organization would like to use RBE, it would create their own GCP project and publish their own custom docker image for building/testing Gerrit eco-system.

The plugin API project is only for usage of Gerrit maintainers and GerritForge CI. Already Zuul CI is using his own Zuul-CI project, so even there we would have to publish a different custom docker image. 

In any event, we must get OK from GCP stake holders before doing that.
